ElementDescription: The NDAR Global Unique Identifier (GUID) for research subject
Subject ID how it's defined in lab/project
Date on which the interview/genetic test/sampling/imaging/biospecimen was completed. MM/DD/YYYY
Age in months at the time of the interview/test/sampling/imaging.
Notes: Age is rounded to chronological month. If the research participant is 15-days-old at time of interview, the appropriate value would be 0 months. If the participant is 16-days-old, the value would be 1 month.

ElementDescription: Sex of subject at birth
Notes: M = Male; F = Female; O=Other; NR = Not reported

ElementDescription: In your household, how many of the following is/are there? Cars for private/personal use (do not consider cars that are used for commercial/professional purposes)
Notes: 0 = none; 3 = one; 7 = two; 10 = three; 13 = four or more

ElementDescription: In your household, how many of the following is/are there? Housekeepers or other employees (that work at least 5 days/week)
Notes: 0 = none; 3 = one; 7 = two; 10 = three; 13 = four or more

ElementDescription: In your household, how many of the following is/are there? Washing machines, excluding tub washing machines
Notes: 0 = none; 2 = one; 4 = two; 5 = three; 6 = four or more

ElementDescription: In your household, how many of the following is/are there? Bathrooms, restrooms, or powder rooms
Notes: 0 - none; 3 = one; 7 = two; 10 = three; 14 = four or more

ElementDescription: In your household, how many of the following is/are there? DVD players or other devices capable of playing DVDs (including videogames and computers), excluding car DVD players
Notes: 0 = none; 1 = one; 3 = two; 4 = three; 6 = four or more

ElementDescription: In your household, how many of the following is/are there? Refrigerators
Notes: 0 = none; 2 = one; 3 = two; 5 = three; 6 = four or more

ElementDescription: In your household, how many of the following is/are there? Freezers
Notes: 0 = none; 2 = one; 4 = two; 5 = three; 6 = four or more

ElementDescription: In your household, how many of the following is/are there? Computers, including desktop computers, laptops, notebooks and netbooks, and excluding tablets, palmtops, or smartphones
Notes: 0 = none; 3 = one; 5 = two; 8 = three; 11 = four or more

ElementDescription: In your household, how many of the following is/are there? Dishwashers
Notes: 0 = none; 3 = one; 4 = two or more

ElementDescription: In your household, how many of the following is/are there? Microwaves/microwave ovens
Notes: 0 = none; 2 = one; 4 = two; 5 = three; 6 = four or more

ElementDescription: In your household, how many of the following is/are there? Motorcycles for private use (do not consider motorcycles that are used for commercial/professional purposes)
Notes: 0 = none; 1 = one; 2 = two; 3 = three; 4 = four or more

ElementDescription: In your household, how many of the following is/are there? Clothes dryers, including washers-and-dryers
Notes: 0 = none; 2 = one; 3 = two; 4 = three; 5 = four or more

ElementDescription: Where does the water come from in your house?
Notes: 0 = Other; 1 = Well, spring, or river; 4 = Water supplier (pipes) or utility company distribution system

ElementDescription: How is the street that you live?
Notes: 0 = Dirt/gravel road; 2 = Asphalt/paved

ElementDescription: What is the father's highest academic degree?
Notes: 0 = Illiterate, no schooling, or incomplete elementary school; 1 = Elementary school diploma, incomplete junior high/middle school; 2 = Junior high/middle school diploma, incomplete high school; 4 = High school diploma, incomplete higher education/college; 7 = Higher education/college degree

ElementDescription: What is the mother's highest academic degree?
Notes: 0 = Illiterate, no schooling, or incomplete elementary school; 1 = Elementary school diploma, incomplete junior high/middle school; 2 = Junior high/middle school diploma, incomplete high school; 4 = High school diploma, incomplete higher education/college; 7 = Higher education/college degree

ElementDescription: Who brings the highest income to the family?
Notes: 1 = father; 2 = mother; 3 = other

ElementDescription: What his/her highest academic degree?
Notes: 0 = Illiterate, no schooling, or incomplete elementary school; 1 = Elementary school diploma, incomplete junior high/middle school; 2 = Junior high/middle school diploma, incomplete high school; 4 = High school diploma, incomplete higher education/college; 7 = Higher education/college degree

ElementDescription: Total ABEP score
Notes: Sum of all the items. Only sum the points related to the highest academic degree of the relative that brings the highest income to the family, i.e. one of abepescola_p, abepescola_m, or abepescola_c corresponding to the figure named in abepchefe

ElementDescription: Socioeconomic class, according to ABEP
ValueRange: A; B1; B2; C1; C2; D-E
